3ï¸âƒ£ Circular Linked List in Java
ğŸ“Œ Difference from Singly/Doubly Linked List?
In Circular Linked List, the last node connects back to the first.
No NULL at the end like in singly/doubly lists.

Circular Linked List Example
HEAD â†’ [10 | Next] â†’ [20 | Next] â†’ [30 | Next] â†» HEAD



Time Complexity of Linked List Operations
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Operation	        Singly Linked List	Doubly Linked List	Circular Linked List
----------------   --------------------  ------------------  ---------------------
Insertion (at end)	    O(n)	               O(n)	               O(n)
Deletion (from end)	    O(n)	               O(n)	               O(n)
Traversal	            O(n)	               O(n)	               O(n)
Searching	            O(n)	               O(n)                O(n)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Advantages of Linked Lists
âœ… Dynamic Size: No need to pre-allocate memory.
âœ… Efficient Insertions/Deletions: No shifting needed like in arrays.
âœ… Useful for Stacks, Queues, and Graphs.

Disadvantages of Linked Lists
âŒ More Memory Usage: Needs extra pointers (Next/Prev).
âŒ No Direct Access: Unlike arrays (arr[i]), you must traverse nodes.
âŒ More Complex than Arrays: Code implementation is longer.

When to Use Linked List?
âœ… When frequent insertions/deletions are needed (e.g., stacks, queues).
âœ… When memory allocation is unpredictable.
âœ… When implementing graphs, hash chains, etc.

When NOT to Use Linked List?
âŒ When you need fast random access (Arrays are better).
âŒ When memory is limited (Linked lists need extra space).

Final Thought ğŸ’­
Linked Lists are powerful but complex!
They are great when you need dynamic memory allocation and frequent insertions/deletions. But for fast access, arrays are better! ğŸš€